{
  "texts": [
    "This clear mismatch between individual preferences and aggregate outcomes is a classic example of emergence.",
    "The second model is a predator-prey model [39,43], describing the ecological dynamics between two interacting species, with one acting as predator and the other as prey, similarly to the Lotka-Volterra equations.",
    "In this ABM, Z t includes agent position and type (prey-predator), while Θ governs the probability to move, reproduce, or die.",
    "This model replicates the cyclical predator-prey population dynamics, typical of Lotka-Volterra systems, while also capturing complex spatial patterns reminiscent of spatial evolutionary games [27].",
    "Both the Schelling and predator-prey models are widely recognized as canonical ABMs and are frequently used as testbeds for the development of novel calibration and surrogate techniques [37,16,23,39,40,26].ABMs have traditionally been powerful for theory generation, but in recent years, they have become increasingly data-driven [29]."
  ]
}